An Anonymous Epistle os Dido to Aeneas

Membra manusque tuas miseramque tumentibus undis Praecipitare diem, poteram crescentis Iuli

Rumpere fata manu parvumque resolvere corpus Morte gravi mersumque in viscera figere ferrum

Vel dare membra feris; sed nostro pectore pulsum Cessit amore nefas, et honesta pericula passus

Corda ligavit amor. Quis tantum in hospite vellet Hoc audere nefas? Quis vota nocentis habere?

manus seems to be added to membra only to make an alliterative phrase ' though it may have been suggested by Ovid’s account of the killing o Absyrtus by Medea, where the hands are mentioned particularly; cf Trist. 3. 9. 27—30 Atque ita divellit, divulsaque membra per aoros Dissipat, in multis invenienda locis; Neu pater iqnoret, scopulo proponit in alto Pallentesque manus, sanquineumque caput.

miseram diem: day of death. Miser is found in inscriptions referring to the dead. Cf. Isid. Ori9. 10. 173 Miser—-secundum autem Cicer- onem proprie mortuus, qui in Tusculanis miseros mortuos vocat, propter quod iam amiserunt vitam. Cf. Cic. Tusc. 1. 9.

Praecipitare: cf. Quint. Decl. 4. 10 Miraris quod suprema mea ipse prae· cipitem. Lucan. 7. 51-2 sua quisque ac publica sata Praecipitare cupit.

crescentis: cf. Verg. Ecl. 7. 25 hedera crescentem ornate poetam. Verg. Aen 4. 274 Ascanium surqentem et spes heredis Iuli. Ov. M et. 14. 583 opibus crescentis Iuli.

Rumpere sata: break off the thread of life spun by the Fates. Cf. Verg. Aen. 4. 631 I nvisam quaerens quam primum abrumpere lucem. Sil. 6. 510—11 vel si stat rumpere vitam In patria moriamur.

7. 33 Hic ardens extrema malis et rumpere vitam.
